ID  - 20059655
T1  - PCOS and urethrovaginal space: 3-D volumetric and vascular analysis.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1111/j.1743-6109.2009.01651.x
A1  - Battaglia, Cesare
A1  - Nappi, Rossella Elena
A1  - Mancini, Fulvia
A1  - Alvisi, Stefania
A1  - Del Forno, Simona
A1  - Battaglia, Bruno
A1  - Venturoli, Stefano
Y1  - 2010//
Y2  - 20100106//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: The vaginal orgasm seems to be evocated by the stimulation of the G-spot: a highly sensitive area on the anterior wall of the human vagina. However, the existence of such a spot is controversial., AIM: To evaluate, by the use of three-dimensional (3-D) ultrasonography, the anatomic structures of the urethrovaginal space both in polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) patients and eumenorrheic non-hirsute controls., METHODS: Twenty-three (Group I) PCOS patients and 25 eumenorrheic young women (Group II) were submitted to two-dimensional (2-D) and 3-D ultrasonography and color Doppler analysis of the urethrovaginal space and of the clitoris., MAIN OUTCOME MEASURES: 2-D ultrasonographic evaluation of the ovaries and of the urethrovaginal space; color Doppler evaluation of the ovarian stromal arteries, urethrovaginal main feeding artery, and dorsal clitoral arteries; 3-D volume calculation of the urethrovaginal space, and 3-D power Doppler analysis of the vascularization index; flow index; and vascularization flow index; hormonal evaluation., RESULTS: The vaginal orgasm was present in 13/23 (56%) patients in PCOS Group and in 13/25 (52%) in the controls. The 3-D reconstruction of the urethrovaginal space demonstrated a gland-like aspect with small feeding vessels: "female prostate." The 3-D mean volume of the "female prostate" was significantly higher in Group I (0.48 +/- 0.21 mL) than in Group II (0.39 +/- 0.19 mL; P = 0.044). The Virtual Organ Computer-aided AnaLys (VOCAL) built mean volume of the "female prostate" was positively correlated with the time since intercourse (r = 0.486; P = 0.032), with the total length of the urethrovaginal space (r = 0.616; P = 0.025) and with the testosterone (r = 0.424; P = 0.048) circulating values., CONCLUSIONS: The presence of the G-spot and its role in vaginal orgasm remains controversial. In Italians, and normal weight PCOS patients the hyperandrogenism seems to result in ovarian stromal and "female prostate" hyperplasia. Copyright © 2010 International Society for Sexual Medicine.
